        "answer_count": 3,
        "title": "java dynamic memory allocation?",
        "body": "<p>Why is an object initialization using the <code>new<\/code> keyword called dynamic memory allocation, since compile time itself we need to know the memory needed for that object. <\/p>\n\n<p>Also please explain what happens when you do <code>ClassA object = new ClassA();<\/code> in <em>heap<\/em> and <em>stack<\/em> .<\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 2532767,
        "tags": [
            "java",
            "memory-management",
            "instantiation"
        ],
        "score": 6,
        "is_answered": true,
        "view_count": 39090,
        "last_edit_date": 1505204630
    },
    "question_comments": [],
    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/965220a70d38e6a29466f44cdb4f804e?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 114848,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 301832,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/301832/donal-fellows",
                "reputation": 138922,
                "display_name": "Donal Fellows",
                "accept_rate": 60
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 10,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1269777358,
            "creation_date": 1269777358,
            "body": "<p><em>All<\/em> Java objects are dynamically allocated. You're always passing around references to them. This is how the language is designed. When you do:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>ClassA obj = new ClassA();\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Then the object is allocated on the heap and a reference to it is stored on the stack (assuming that's inside a method, of course). What this means is that you can always pass objects about without worrying about where they are stored.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 2532773,
            "question_id": 2532767
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c53d539b59c19087182f0b1c53bb52de?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 7450,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 12960,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/12960/brian-agnew",
                "reputation": 273383,
                "display_name": "Brian Agnew"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 6,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1269777360,
            "creation_date": 1269777360,
            "body": "<p>It's dynamic since you don't know <em>when<\/em> it needs allocating - you allocate upon demand. <\/p>\n\n<p>Note also that you know how much memory that object requires, but not how much <em>that object's members require<\/em>. This may only be determinable at run time (e.g. an array of variable size).<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 2532774,
            "question_id": 2532767
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/CpXf1Drk.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 6339179,
